{
  "Which tool is used to measure the mass of an object?": "",
  "A graduated cylinder": "",
  "A balance or scale": "",
  "A metric ruler tool": "",
  "A thermometer device": "",
  "A balance or scale is used to measure mass. A triple-beam balance and an electronic balance are common laboratory tools for this purpose. Mass is typically measured in grams or kilograms.": "",
  "What tool is used to measure the volume of a liquid?": "",
  "A ruler": "",
  "A balance": "",
  "A thermometer": "",
  "A graduated cylinder is a tall, narrow container with measurement markings used to measure liquid volume accurately. Volume is typically measured in milliliters (mL) or liters (L).": "",
  "What is the correct way to read the volume of liquid in a graduated cylinder?": "",
  "Read the level at the top of the curved surface of the liquid": "",
  "Read the level at the bottom of the meniscus at eye level": "",
  "Read the level from above looking straight down into the liquid": "",
  "Read the level at the highest point the liquid touches the glass": "",
  "When reading a graduated cylinder, your eyes should be level with the liquid surface, and you read at the bottom of the meniscus (the curved surface of the liquid). This gives the most accurate reading.": "",
  "Which tool measures temperature?": "",
  "A barometer instrument": "",
  "A spring scale device": "",
  "A thermometer measures temperature. In science, temperature is usually measured in degrees Celsius (°C). The liquid or digital sensor inside the thermometer responds to heat changes.": "",
  "What unit is used when measuring length with a metric ruler?": "",
  "Grams or kilograms": "",
  "Liters or milliliters": "",
  "Centimeters or millimeters": "",
  "Degrees Celsius or Kelvin": "",
  "A metric ruler measures length in centimeters (cm) and millimeters (mm). The larger marks are centimeters, and the smaller marks between them are millimeters (10 mm = 1 cm).": "",
  "What is a triple-beam balance used to measure?": "",
  "Temperature in Celsius": "",
  "Mass in grams": "",
  "Volume in milliliters": "",
  "Length in centimeters": "",
  "A triple-beam balance measures mass in grams. It has three beams with sliding weights (riders). You add the readings from all three beams to find the total mass.": "",
  "A spring scale measures which property?": "",
  "Mass of an object": "",
  "Force or weight of an object": "",
  "Volume of a liquid sample": "",
  "Temperature of a substance": "",
  "A spring scale measures force, typically weight (the force of gravity on an object). It works by stretching a spring — the more force applied, the more the spring stretches. Force is measured in newtons (N).": "",
  "What is the smallest division on most metric rulers?": "",
  "1 centimeter": "",
  "1 millimeter": "",
  "1 meter": "",
  "1 decimeter": "",
  "Most metric rulers have markings down to 1 millimeter (the small lines between centimeter marks). This allows measurements to be estimated to the nearest 0.5 mm or 0.1 mm.": "",
  "What does a stopwatch measure?": "",
  "Distance traveled by an object": "",
  "Time elapsed during an event": "",
  "Speed of a moving object along a path": "",
  "Force applied to a specific object": "",
  "A stopwatch measures elapsed time — how long an event takes from start to finish. Time is typically measured in seconds (s), minutes (min), or hours (h).": "",
  "Which measuring tool would you use to find the length of a desk?": "",
  "A meter stick or tape measure": "",
  "A triple-beam balance tool": "",
  "A thermometer instrument": "",
  "A meter stick or tape measure is the best tool for measuring the length of a desk. A standard ruler (30 cm) would be too short, while a meter stick (100 cm) or tape measure can cover the full length.": "",
  "What is a meniscus?": "",
  "The curved surface of a liquid in a container, caused by surface tension": "",
  "A type of measuring tool used to determine the mass of solid objects": "",
  "The scale markings printed on the side of a graduated cylinder tool": "",
  "A unit of measurement equal to one thousandth of a liter of liquid": "",
  "A meniscus is the curved surface of a liquid in a container. Water forms a concave (dip-down) meniscus because it is attracted to glass. Always read the volume at the bottom of the meniscus.": "",
  "What is a graduated cylinder?": "",
  "A tall, narrow container with measurement markings used to measure liquid volume": "",
  "A flat, wide instrument used to measure the temperature of liquids and gases": "",
  "A balance with three beams used to measure the mass of objects in grams": "",
  "A ruler with both metric and customary markings for measuring length values": "",
  "A graduated cylinder is a tall, narrow glass or plastic tube marked with measurement lines (graduations) used to accurately measure liquid volume in milliliters (mL).": "",
  "What is a beaker used for in the lab?": "",
  "A wide-mouthed container used for mixing, heating, and holding liquids approximately": "",
  "A precision instrument used to measure exact volumes of liquids to the nearest drop": "",
  "A tool specifically designed to measure the mass of small solid objects precisely": "",
  "A narrow tube used to transfer small amounts of liquid between two containers": "",
  "A beaker is a wide-mouthed glass container used for mixing, stirring, and heating liquids. While it has measurement markings, they are approximate — a graduated cylinder should be used for precise volume measurements.": "",
  "What does 'calibrate' mean for a measuring instrument?": "",
  "To adjust an instrument so it gives accurate readings compared to a known standard": "",
  "To clean an instrument thoroughly before using it for the first time in a lab": "",
  "To break an instrument down into its individual parts for storage purposes": "",
  "To record the serial number and brand name of an instrument in a notebook": "",
  "Calibrating means adjusting an instrument so it gives correct readings. For example, zeroing a balance before use ensures it reads 0 grams when empty. Proper calibration is essential for accurate measurements.": "",
  "What does 'resolution' mean for a measuring tool?": "",
  "The smallest measurement increment that the tool can detect or display": "",
  "The maximum value that the measuring tool is able to measure overall": "",
  "The speed at which the measuring tool provides its reading to the user": "",
  "The physical size and weight of the measuring tool being used in the lab": "",
  "Resolution is the smallest change a measuring tool can detect. A ruler marked in millimeters has a resolution of 1 mm, while one marked only in centimeters has a resolution of 1 cm. Higher resolution means more detailed measurements.": "",
  "What does 'parallax error' mean?": "",
  "A reading error caused by viewing a measurement from an angle instead of straight on": "",
  "An error caused by using a broken or damaged instrument during a measurement": "",
  "An error that occurs when the wrong units are recorded in the data table": "",
  "An error caused by forgetting to calibrate an instrument before taking a reading": "",
  "Parallax error occurs when you read an instrument from an angle rather than straight on. Looking at a graduated cylinder from above or below will give an inaccurate reading. Always read at eye level.": "",
  "What does 'significant figures' mean for measurements?": "",
  "All the digits in a measurement that are certain, plus one estimated digit": "",
  "Only the digits that appear after the decimal point in a measured value": "",
  "The total number of zeros in a measurement regardless of their position": "",
  "The units attached to a numerical value in a scientific measurement": "",
  "Significant figures include all certain digits plus one estimated digit. They communicate measurement precision. For example, 12.5 cm has three significant figures — the 1 and 2 are certain, and the 5 is estimated.": "",
  "What does 'analog' mean for a measuring instrument?": "",
  "An instrument that uses a physical display like a needle or liquid column to show readings": "",
  "An instrument that displays exact numerical values on an electronic screen": "",
  "An instrument that must be connected to a computer to function at all": "",
  "An instrument that automatically records and stores data in its memory": "",
  "An analog instrument uses a continuous physical display — like a moving needle, liquid column, or dial — to show measurements. A mercury thermometer and a dial scale are analog instruments.": "",
  "What does 'digital' mean for a measuring instrument?": "",
  "An instrument that displays readings as exact numbers on an electronic screen": "",
  "An instrument that uses a needle or liquid column to show the measurement": "",
  "An instrument that can only be used by touching it with your bare fingers": "",
  "An instrument that measures only digital information like computer file sizes": "",
  "A digital instrument shows measurements as numbers on an electronic display. Digital thermometers, electronic balances, and digital stopwatches are common examples. They are often easier to read than analog instruments.": "",
  "What does 'estimate' mean when reading a measurement?": "",
  "Determining the value between the smallest markings on a measuring tool": "",
  "Guessing a measurement without using any instrument at all during the lab": "",
  "Rounding a measurement to the nearest whole number for easier recording": "",
  "Using a calculator to convert the measurement into different unit values": "",
  "Estimating means determining a value between the smallest marked divisions on a tool. If a ruler shows marks every millimeter and the object falls between two marks, you estimate the last digit.": "",
  "A student needs to measure exactly 25.0 mL of water for an experiment. Which tool should she use?": "",
  "A 250 mL beaker with approximate markings on the side": "",
  "A 50 mL graduated cylinder with precise markings": "",
  "A large bucket filled with water from the classroom sink": "",
  "A kitchen measuring cup borrowed from the cafeteria": "",
  "A graduated cylinder provides the most precise volume measurement. Beakers have approximate markings and are not accurate enough for precise measurements. A 50 mL graduated cylinder is ideal for measuring 25.0 mL.": "",
  "A student reads a graduated cylinder from above and gets 43 mL. When she reads at eye level, she gets 42 mL. What caused the difference?": "",
  "The liquid evaporated between the two readings she took quickly": "",
  "Parallax error from reading the meniscus at an incorrect angle": "",
  "The graduated cylinder is defective and should be replaced now": "",
  "The liquid expanded due to the heat from her hand on the glass": "",
  "Looking from above creates parallax error — the measurement appears higher than it actually is. The correct reading (42 mL) comes from viewing the bottom of the meniscus at eye level.": "",
  "A student places an object on a triple-beam balance. The riders read: 100 g beam = 200 g, 10 g beam = 30 g, 1 g beam = 5.5 g. What is the mass of the object?": "",
  "200.355 g": "",
  "235.5 g": "",
  "230.5 g": "",
  "205.3 g": "",
  "Add the readings from all three beams: 200 + 30 + 5.5 = 235.5 g. This is the total mass of the object.": "",
  "A student wants to measure how long it takes a ball to roll down a ramp. Which tool is most appropriate?": "",
  "A thermometer to track temperature changes": "",
  "A stopwatch to time the ball's travel duration": "",
  "A graduated cylinder to measure liquid volume": "",
  "A triple-beam balance to measure the ball's mass": "",
  "A stopwatch is the correct tool for measuring elapsed time. The student would start the stopwatch when the ball begins moving and stop it when the ball reaches the bottom of the ramp.": "",
  "A student measures the length of a pencil as 18.3 cm using a ruler. Her partner measures the same pencil and gets 18.5 cm. What is the most likely reason for the difference?": "",
  "The pencil grew 0.2 cm between the two measurements taken by each student": "",
  "Different estimation of the last digit between the ruler's smallest markings": "",
  "The ruler shrank between the two measurements taken in the same laboratory": "",
  "One student used a metric ruler while the other used a customary ruler": "",
  "The last digit (0.3 vs. 0.5) is estimated between the ruler's smallest markings. Different people may estimate this value slightly differently. This is normal and shows measurement uncertainty.": "",
  "A student needs to determine the weight (force of gravity) on a rock. Which tool should she use?": "",
  "A triple-beam balance that measures in grams": "",
  "A spring scale that measures in newtons": "",
  "A meter stick that measures in centimeters": "",
  "A graduated cylinder that measures in milliliters": "",
  "A spring scale measures weight (force) in newtons. A balance measures mass in grams. Weight and mass are different — mass is the amount of matter, while weight is the gravitational force on that mass.": "",
  "A student measures the temperature of water before and after heating it. The thermometer shows the temperature went from 22°C to 78°C. What was the temperature change?": "",
  "100°C change": "",
  "56°C change": "",
  "22°C change": "",
  "78°C change": "",
  "The temperature change is 78°C − 22°C = 56°C. The water temperature increased by 56 degrees Celsius during the heating process.": "",
  "A student tries to measure the volume of a small irregular rock. She cannot use a ruler because the rock is not a regular shape. What method should she use?": "",
  "Place it on a balance and read the volume from the mass reading directly": "",
  "Use water displacement in a graduated cylinder to find the volume": "",
  "Estimate the volume by looking at the rock and guessing its size by eye": "",
  "Measure the temperature of the rock and convert it to a volume reading": "",
  "Water displacement is the correct method. Fill a graduated cylinder partway with water, record the volume, then carefully add the rock. The difference between the two water levels equals the rock's volume.": "",
  "A student puts an empty beaker on a balance and reads 120 g. She then fills the beaker with water and reads 370 g. What is the mass of the water alone?": "",
  "370 g of water": "",
  "250 g of water": "",
  "120 g of water": "",
  "490 g of water": "",
  "Subtract the mass of the empty beaker from the total: 370 g − 120 g = 250 g. The mass of the water alone is 250 grams. This technique of subtracting the container mass is called 'taring.'": "",
  "A student's electronic balance shows 15.23 g for a sample, but the teacher's calibrated balance shows 15.00 g. What should the student suspect about her balance?": "",
  "Her balance is more accurate because it shows more decimal places in the reading": "",
  "Her balance may need to be calibrated because it reads 0.23 g higher than expected": "",
  "The teacher's balance must be wrong because electronic balances are always correct": "",
  "Both balances are equally correct since all measurements have some small variation": "",
  "A consistent discrepancy of 0.23 g suggests the student's balance may need calibration. Since the teacher's balance is known to be calibrated (the reference standard), the student's balance is likely reading high.": ""
}